      "id": 1,
      "text": "Hillsborough CDP sits in a township chartered May 29 1771, likely named after Wills Hill, the Earl of Hillsborough.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/hillsborough_cdp_new_jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Archaeological finds show Unami Lenape Indians occupied the Hillsborough area over 10,000 years ago, including Clovis spear points.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/hillsborough_cdp_new_jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Duke Farms, a 2,700‑acre estate once owned by tobacco magnate James Buchanan Duke, now hosts gardens and wildlife in Hillsborough.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6,
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hillsborough_Township%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "During the Revolutionary War, General George Washington marched from Princeton through Hillsborough toward Morristown, using the valley’s terrain for training.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11,
        27
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hillsborough_Township%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The Norfolk Southern Lehigh Line cuts through Hillsborough, a remnant of the historic Lehigh Valley Railroad that once linked the region to the Northeast.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        13
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hillsborough_Township%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Hillsborough’s original royal charter issued May 31 1771 was revoked and revised on September 12 1771, solidifying its township status.",
